description: Traditional flavors from two distinct cultures, Jewish and Japanese, intersect in Williamsburg. With joyful service and a beautiful ambiance, this spot is underhyped and worth every visit.
Romantic, old-school piano lounge with a dress code, plus cocktails & fancy bites like caviar.
The eclectic menu has a Mediterranean slant at this small, airy bistro with booths & a bar.
Seasonal dishes served in a hip, modern restaurant & wine bar that has a covered terrace.
Natural, biodynamic & small-production wines are paired with market-driven fare in a sleek setting.
An intimate, 20-seat restaurant by its three partners Clay Castillo, Gabriel Merino and Executive Chef Charlie Mitchell.

The beloved destination for Italian American food from the same team behind Carbone is finally back, and while the mozzarella is still flowing, it’s not quite the same as you might remember; it’s even better.
Neighborhood wine bar with a romantic vibe, offering traditional Italian food & a robust wine list.
Serene joint with a classy vibe offering small plates & full meals with matching wines.
Wine bar from James Murphy of LCD Soundsystem serving small plates in snug digs with light woodwork.
Italian small plates are matched by an extensive wine list at this bi-level restaurant.
Lively, colorful, and bad in the... best way.

A speakeasy omakase that has probably popped up in you social media feed at some point in the last year or so. If you can get a reservation (and that's a big if), punch in the code and enjoy the ride. Reservations open up a month in advance.

A dreamy, dimly lit Italian bar with amazing wine and inventive menu. Think pastas like sunchoke caramelle or veal agnolotti with amaretto, and snacks like polenta with Maine sea urchin and grilled tripe with pecorino and mint. Great date spot.
Popular, quaint bistro offering a French small-plates menu at breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
Two-story spot in a former opera house, offering contemporary Chinese dishes & stylish touches.
Venerated, iconic eatery serving raw oysters, pan roasts & chowders in a bustling, vaulted setting.
Italian trattoria serving traditional plates & apéritifs in a rustic, cozy space.
Popular place for Mediterranean inspired menu, including gravy meatball sliders and spiced sugar beignets.
Legendary circa-1915 cafe serving small plates & cocktails in an updated historic setting.
High-end takes on red-sauce fare await at this A-lister Italian restaurant in a retro-glam space.
You know the Smith. Solid, consistent, always busy, casual American brasserie, a great spot for classic choices: martini, steak, salmon, mussels.
Oysters, cocktails & small plates in a New Orleans-styled setting with an atmospheric garden.
Sophisticated Japanese eatery offering charcoal-grilled skewers & sake, plus a chef's-choice option.
Upscale scene where an international crowd tucks into Italian food chased with Bellinis.
Sophisticated French cooking presented in chic, airy environs with salvaged-wood beams.
Iconic French brasserie with steak frites, brunch & pastries in a classy space with red banquettes.
Upscale chophouse chain serving dry-aged steaks, seafood & wine in an elegant setting.
Counter-service pizzeria known for classic New York slices since 1975.

Designed by renowned architect Philippe Starck, the restaurant spans two floors with a French art deco-inspired dining room and Le Chalet—a bar and lounge offering cozy, après-ski style interiors and outdoor terrace overlooking 5th avenue.
Clubby Irish gastropub with an extensive beer menu featuring craft, domestic & international brews.

This spot serves up a burger that's all the rave, complete with a mountain of fries. Reservations might run late, so patience is key. The mac and cheese is popular, but opinions vary. Service shines, especially with servers like Sofia, who ensure a top-notch experience. Don't miss the Smith burger and vanilla ice cream, and definitely check out the quirky Photo Booth in the bathroom. Prices are on the higher side, and while some dishes, like shrimp grits, might disappoint, the overall vibe and kid-friendly atmosphere with fun games make it worth a visit. Perfect for brunch with standout dishes like the ranchero scramble and pancakes.
Contemporary French eatery, pastry counter, and home decor showcase inside Roman and Williams Guild.
New American fare served from breakfast to late-night in a rustic space with just a few tables.
Rustic-chic French cafe serving traditional fare including brunch with wine & classic cocktails.
Farm-to-table American restaurant for dinner and weekend brunch, with private dining rooms located inside a historic brownstone.
Simple eatery with an industrial vibe fixing up generous subs, including vegetarian & vegan options.
Japanese small plates & a deep sake list in a blond-wood izakaya hidden beneath an office building.
Cocktails and Asian fusion eats are offered in this chic eatery with a patio.
Contemporary bistro serving French cuisine and natural wines in a sophisticated environment.

You’ll want to put this stylish addition to the ever-growing Manhattan French restaurant scene on your personal hit list. Chef Mitsunobu Nagae is a veteran of the Joël Robuchon empire, and it shows in his elegant Japanese-accented Gallic fare — whether his multi-course tasting menu or the short à la carte selection rich with luxury ingredients like foie gras, lobster, and caviar.

Chef Austin Johnson, a veteran of Eleven Madison Park and Paris’ Frenchie, gives a whole new meaning to “farm to table.” Here, the tables are filled with produce from this vegetable-forward restaurant’s own farm in upstate New York, and Johnson decides what gets planted.
Historical 1810 bi-level townhouse showcases New American fare in a dimly lit, rustic setting.
Cozy, wood-accented eatery serving a varied, seasonally changing menu of comfort food dishes.
American fare, craft cocktails & Colonial tavern decor draws a hip crowd to this hidden-away spot.
Relaxed spot dishing up Southwestern eats, including breakfast burritos & green chile cheeseburgers.
French bistro basics & a Parisian vibe enliven this tiny BYO restaurant with sidewalk seating.
Serves Italian-American classics with wine and cocktails in a marble-accented space.

With a roster of neighborhood favorites already under his belt (The Clam, Market Table), chef Mike Price delivers another well-tuned concept in the Mary Lane, where seasonal cuisine shines. Think the greenmarkets' best-in-class produce and a menu built on comfort.

Supper club with Jazz Age-themed decor, a long cocktail list & nightly live music performances.
Busy Japanese joint specializing in rice bowls & ramen noodle dishes in a casual atmosphere.
Buzzy Japanese restaurant serving sushi, steak & other traditional entrees since 1984.

11 Tigers is a speakeasy to know should you be out drinking in the East Village. Not only for its yadong-infused cocktails (a reputed Thai herbal liqueur), but for its exciting izakaya menu, where the cuisines of Japan and Thailand collide to delicious effect — think tom yum ramen, drunken (udon) noodles, and the like.
Classic Moroccan flavors & outdoor seating draw a bohemian crowd to this neighborhood standby.
Serves diner food including pancakes and cheeseburgers with international influences, plus counter seating available.
Converted auto-body shop offering wood-fired Italian fare, housemade pastas, and cocktails.
Restaurant for seasonal, shareable Peruvian dishes & Latin cocktails.

Because yubu tarts from the critically acclaimed team behind Korean Chinese spot Joomak Banjum can’t be beat. Ddobar also serves an affordable 13-course omakase at this countertop spot that’s truly inventive and not to be missed.
Bustling New American eatery with huge windows & an emphasis on farm-fresh fare.

When the chef-owner behind Fish Cheeks delves into what Thailand’s royalty and aristocracy feasted on, you pay attention. And such is the case with Kru, which will surprise you with its treasure trove of old Thai recipes you’d be hard-pressed to find anywhere else in New York.
Sprawling spot at the Wythe Hotel serving French fare, wine & cocktails in an easygoing setting.
Grilled whole fish stars on a classic Greek menu at this bright, airy bistro with an expansive wine list.

You’ll feel like you’re on the shores of the Aegean when you settle into your seat in this handsome wood-beamed dining room or, weather permitting, the brick-lined garden with its terra-cotta planters and ornate umbrellas. Avra’s menu offers a wide range of Greek specialties, with the focus definitely on seafood — including impeccable whole fish direct from Grecian waters.
Upscale Greek seafood eatery with fresh fish by the pound, villa decor & expansive outdoor seating.

This massive temple to fresh Greek seafood and specialties occupies the bottom three levels of what was once known as the historic Time/Life building near Rockefeller Center, and the food impresses as much as the spacious environs. Freshly caught whole fish are on abundant display, and you shouldn’t leave without at least one order of the Avra chips: paper-thin slices of fried zucchini and eggplant elegantly layered together atop a crisp white plate.
Straightforward Greek cuisine such as seafood & lamb served in warm digs with exposed-wood beams.
Cozy, charming taverna with a patio for grilled seafood & other Greek island-inspired fare.

Friendly service with a buzzy atmosphere, all in a typical Italian restaurant setting. It is matched by home cooking like you would expect to eat in Italy, which is one of the keys to the success of the restaurant. Fully renovated in 2021 the location looks warm and cozy.

The famed Roscioli in Rome — yes, that one — is now in the heart of New York’s Soho neighborhood, courtesy of what was once one of our favorite dinner party destinations, Niche Niche. Upstairs you’ll find a la carte options and gourmet ingredients galore; downstairs, they serve an incredible tasting menu that shows you exactly why Roscioli is so beloved. Note: reservations are only required for the downstairs tasting menu.

Salil Mehta, the chef and restaurateur behind some of the city’s most celebrated Southeast Asian restaurants (Laut, Laut Singapura, Singlish, and Wau) turns his focus to his hometown of New Delhi, and to street food at this Upper West Side gem with its own tandoor clay oven. Don’t sleep on the dori kebab, the rogan josh made with steak, or the Malabar bone marrow pulau.

Chefs (and brothers) Zhan Chen and Peter Chen have devised a Cantonese American menu that’s both familiar and also unexpected: Think Southern-style scallion biscuits paired with salt-and-pepper chicken, and tiger shrimp with walnuts, tossed in a Calabrian chile aioli.

It would be a travesty not to order one of the expertly made cocktails (zero-proof included) at this rooftop restaurant helmed by a trio of NoMad veterans, as would overlooking the whimsical, creative menu — a personal and lovely ode to the food and culture of Latin American diaspora.
Hip gathering place serving seasonally-driven plates and cocktails along with happy hour.
Theatrical evocation of Paris featuring bistro food & high-energy atmospherics from a chic crowd.

Refined restaurant with outdoor seating serving thoughtfully sourced Mediterranean dishes.

A daily-changing menu of pintxos, mains & desserts is served in a relaxed space with globe lights.

Occupying a dramatic, festive space beneath the catwalk entry of Moxy Lower East Side, Japanese restaurant Sake no Hana serves free-spirited izakaya dishes invigorated with New York attitude. With a shareable menu of grilled teppanyaki dishes, yakitori skewers, Wagyu beef, creative sushi rolls, and a curated list of sakes, beers, and cocktails highlighting Japanese spirits. The space buzzes with alluring energy perfect for any celebration.

You’ll want to share the masterly modern Asian fare at this casually opulent import from Miami — from the crispy rice dishes to the uncommon vegetarian fare to the wood-fired meats — with somebody special.

Tatsuda NYC is a sophisticated harmony of Japanese cuisine and New Yorkers ingenuity. Celebrated for its amusing devotion for sushi and understated elegance, art, and passion in hospitality and modern sensibilities underscore a quintessential dining experience.
Inventive cocktails made with Latin spirits plus Mexican bites in a brick-walled space.
Serves diner food including pancakes and cheeseburgers with international influences, plus counter seating available.
Celebrated, stylish seafood & grill restaurant offshoot with an aperitivo bar & a terrace.

Now here’s a pizzeria with an all-star team in charge: Melissa Rodriguez, former executive chef at the elegantly Italian Del Posto (now closed); and ex-Del Posto general manager Jeff Katz. The two have taken over the old Del Posto space, and Mel’s is just the start of what they plan to do with it. The wood-oven pizzas are irresistible — but save room for a gelato sundae.
Creative Pan-Latin fare served in a lively space with open-window seating & a popular happy hour.
Midcentury style steakhouse in the iconic Seagram Building, serving classic dishes and cocktails.
Old-school waiters set the tone at this longtime Italian restaurant and celebrity hangout.

Ma•dé, from the same duo behind Wayan, takes a global perspective on local fare, drawing inspiration from around the world, including Indonesia, Japan, France, and the Americas. Don’t sleep on the array of seafood dishes from chef Cedric Vongerichten.

heartwarming flavors, tradition, and a deep love for the world of hospitality. Chef Rudy Accornero from "The Eternal City" of Rome has crafted a menu that celebrates the love and passion for food passed down from his beloved grandparents. focus of truffle
Updated Italian dishes plus cocktails & housemade limoncello in spacious, low-key digs.

Serving upscale Oaxaca and Regional Mexican Cuisine with a twist; along with imported artisanal mezcal and tequila handpicked from various regions of Mexico. IXTA Cocina Mexicana + Mezcal Bar located in Manhattan’s lower east side (LES) on Bowery. Get away from the hustle and bustle of New York City and step into the jungle of our enchanted Tulum themed Mexican Restaurant. Combining savory housemade Oaxacan moles and freshly sourced Mexican cuisine created by executive chef Francisco Blanco. Our handcrafted cocktails are artfully created from the finest selection of local and imported liquor, including different selections of mezcal, tequila, and rum—including some specialized IPA and wines from Mexico. All our specialty cocktails are alchemized with exotic herbs and spices, and seasonal fruits.

Because executive chef Shenarri “Greens” Freeman has accomplished the seemingly impossible: a next-level Southern and soul food vegan concept. As part of Ravi DeRossi’s Overthrow Hospitality revamp, Cadence is the culmination of Freeman’s love affair with plant-based cuisine, and her plates — smoked grits, jerk mac and cheese, and the usual suspects — are something else.

Equinox Hotel restaurant for veggie-forward dishes and crudos in a polished venue with a terrace.
Wood-fired pizzas & Italian fare from an open kitchen set in a former body shop in Clinton Hill.

Chef Andrew Carmellini is behind many New Yorkers’ favorite restaurants, from Bar Primi and Locanda Verde to Lafayette, and this restaurant — the first to bear his name — marks his return to fine dining in the luxurious and elegant setting of the Fifth Avenue Hotel. The menu here blends French and Italian influences — everything from sole Normande and squab en croûte to lobster cannelloni with Osetra caviar.

Since 2003, Little Ruby’s Cafe has brought Australian cafe culture to New York City, offering approachable all-day fare, specialty drinks, and a full coffee program. Open for brekkie, lunch and dinner 7 days a week, Little Ruby’s Cafe’s beloved menu features the signature burgers, pastas, salads and brunch classics, all served in thoughtfully designed spaces. Located on the landmark corner of West 4th St & 7th Avenue, our newest Little Ruby’s Cafe features an airy, multi-level space. A first for Little Ruby’s, West Village offers a full bar with an exclusive cocktail program alongside our classic menu with new dishes unique to the location. With an expansive terrace and sweeping windows, the West Village restaurant invites guests to absorb the energy of the neighborhood as they enjoy their morning brekkie or grab cocktails and dinner with friends. Opening October 2023. Little Ruby’s West Village will be open 7 days a week for brekkie, lunch and dinner.

Tonchin has never been quite like other ramen bars to begin with, and the Brooklyn outpost of this Tokyo-based chain proves that perfectly. Come here for all your ramen needs, as well as an extensive list of natural wines and delicious raw bar specialties that you can’t get over in Manhattan, like oysters on the half-shell and bright tartar. Pro tip: Don’t sleep on the vegan salad or the fried chicken wings.

Welcome to the first Cecconi's in Manhattan! Situated on the first floor of the Ned Nomad, this modern-day classic Italian restaurant serves hand-made pasta, wood oven-fired pizza, seafood, and dishes from Northern Italy. Design details include a hand-chipped mosaic and terrazzo striped floor, a new take on the traditional Cecconi’s stripe, set against navy velvet banquettes, golden-yellow leather chairs, and a polished timber bar, inspired by classic mid-century Italian Trattorias. Cecconi’s is open to the public, with advance reservations for members and hotel guests.
